</disciplines><abstract>&lt;p&gt;The &lt;em&gt;zero-divisor graph&lt;/em&gt; of a commutative ring is the graph whose vertices are the nonzero zero-divisors of the ring such that distinct vertices are adjacent if and only if their product is zero. We use this construction to study the interplay between ring-theoretic and graph-theoretic properties. Of particular interest are Boolean rings and commutative rings of quotients.&lt;/p&gt;</abstract>
